Class Person

  • java.lang.Object
    • application.Person
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    Wizard

    public class Person
extends java.lang.Object
    A very basic Person class that describes a generic person as would be used in a Human Resources Application or Video Game Character

    1.0
    Author:

        public Person(java.lang.String fN,
              java.lang.String lN,
              java.lang.String sex,
              byte age)
        A constructor that creates a Person object with the most common properties set at construction time
        Parameters:
        fN - The first or given name of the new Person object
        lN - The last of family name of the new Person object
        sex - The gender or sex of the new Person object (valid values are "male", "female", and "unspecified")
        age - The age in years of the new Person object (age must be a positive integer less than 128)
        Throws:

      • Person

        public Person(java.lang.String fN,
              java.lang.String lN,
              java.lang.String mN,
              java.lang.String title,
              java.lang.String suffix,
              java.lang.String sex,
              byte age)
       throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        A constructor that creates a Person object with all of the properties set at construction time
        Parameters:
        fN - The first or given name of the new Person object
        lN - The last of family name of the new Person object
        mN - The middle name of the new Person object
        title - The courtesy title of the new Person object (valid values are "Mr", "Mrs", "Ms", "Miss", or "Dr")
        suffix - The name suffix of the new Person object (valid values are "Jr", "II", "III", "IV", or "PhD")
        sex - The gender or sex of the new Person object (valid values are "male", "female", and "unspecified")
        age - The age in years of the new Person object (age must be a positive integer less than 128)
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Thrown if the passed in courtesty title is not one of "Mr", "Mrs", "Ms", "Miss", or "Dr"; the passed in name suffix is not one of "Jr", "II", "III", "IV", or "PhD"; gender is not "male", "female", or "unspecified"; or if the age is negative
